<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <%- include('partials/head.ejs') %>

  <body>
    <div id="main_div">
      <%- include('partials/header.ejs') %> <%- include('partials/nav.ejs') %>

      <main class="grid-layout">
        <%- include('partials/left-sidebar.ejs') %>

        <section class="page_content">
          <h2>Popular Websites</h2>
          <figure>
            <img
              src="img/online_now.gif"
              class="computer-gif"
              alt="Early Internet websites"
            />
            <figcaption>
              Many classic websites helped shape online culture in the late
              1990s and early 2000s.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
          <p>
            Before social media became popular, people explored the Internet
            through search engines, personal websites, chat rooms, and online
            communities. Many of these websites introduced new ways to
            communicate, share information, and express creativity. While some
            have disappeared or changed dramatically, they helped build the
            foundation of today's web.
          </p>
          <h3>Yahoo!</h3>
          <p>
            Yahoo! was one of the most popular websites on the Internet. It
            served as both a search engine and a directory where users could
            browse categories such as news, sports, shopping, and entertainment.
            For many people, Yahoo! was their homepage every time they opened a
            web browser.
          </p>
          <h3>AOL Instant Messenger (AIM)</h3>
          <p>
            AIM allowed friends and family to chat with each other in real time.
            Users created screen names, customized away messages, and waited to
            hear the famous notification sound whenever a buddy signed online.
            Instant messaging quickly became one of the most popular ways to
            communicate over the Internet.
          </p>
          <h3>GeoCities</h3>
          <p>
            GeoCities gave anyone the opportunity to build a personal website
            without needing advanced programming knowledge. Many pages featured
            colorful backgrounds, animated GIFs, visitor counters, guestbooks,
            and flashing text. It became one of the most recognizable examples
            of early web design.
          </p>
          <h3>Napster</h3>
          <p>
            Napster changed the way people shared music online by allowing users
            to exchange MP3 files directly with one another. Although it became
            involved in major copyright lawsuits, it introduced many people to
            peer-to-peer file sharing and influenced future online music
            services.
          </p>
          <h3>MySpace</h3>
          <p>
            Launched in the early 2000s, MySpace became one of the first major
            social networking websites. Users could customize their profile
            pages with music, colors, images, and HTML, making every profile
            unique. It helped pave the way for modern social media platforms.
          </p>
        </section>

        <%- include('partials/right-sidebar.ejs') %>
      </main>

      <%- include('partials/footer.ejs') %>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
